# Intro sequence dialogue.
# Format: see data/dialogue/school.dlg.

[exposition]
Uncle: You're up early.
You: Yeah, I've gotta get to class.
Uncle: Right. Factory tomorrow then.
You: That's the deal...
Uncle: Good. Patrol drones made two passes over the block last night. Nothing came of it, but they're getting curious again. You should keep your head down.
You: Should I be worried?
Uncle: You should. Be quiet and punctual. Worry's expensive.
You: Almost as expensive as rent.
Uncle: The arrangement's fair. I keep the roof over your head, you pull your weight. Food, heat, power- none of it runs free.
You: Dad left money.
Uncle: Tuition. He had it set aside- just enough for your credits. That's what he left. Everything else is yours to sort out now. You're an adult now.
You: Then I guess I have to work...
Uncle: Yes, you will. You keep your head down in class, you pull your weight at the factory, we both win.
You: That's the speech?
Uncle: That's the generous version. The other one has a spreadsheet. Get to class.

[evening_room]
Uncle: Kid, I need you to pick up some parts from Ed's shop.
You: What? Why me?
Uncle: Because you work for me now.
You: I thought factory tomorrow meant factory tomorrow.
Uncle: Consider it part of the job.
You: Fine... What parts?
Uncle: Small stuff. Extra parts. Mostly.
You: Mostly?
Uncle: Ed knows what to give you. Go before he closes.

[store_intro]
Parts on every surface. Most of it shouldn't be on display.
You thought about the drone on the way over. You're still not sure you picked the right routes to avoid them.
A man appears from the back. He doesn't introduce himself. It's probably Ed.
"Parts or browsing?" he asks gruffly.
You tell him your uncle sent you.
He nods. That's apparently enough.

[store_outro]
Ed retreats back into his office before you've finished zipping your bag. A click sounds from the door as he locks it behind him.
Your backpack is heavier than you expected. The walk home is not fun.
You drop everything off with your uncle.
Uncle: Hey, good job Kid. Keep it up and you might get a raise.
You: You don't mean that.
Uncle: Yeah... I don't.
[i]He sits up and reaches over to the backpack.[/i]
Uncle: Alright, scram. I don't want you involved in this part of the business.
You finally head to your room.

[bedroom_night]
Without that backpack on, you feel light as a feather.
It's been a long day. The bed looks really comfy.
Tomorrow will be factory work...

[school_second]
The next morning, class feels easier to sit through because there is something waiting after it.
You take notes. You answer when called on. You do enough to look like you belong there.
The trick is not acting innocent. The trick is acting busy.

[robot_first_talk]
The head goes still after the test.
For a second, you just listen to the shed cooling down around it.
"...hello?"
The voice is small, careful, and very real.
You lean closer before you can talk yourself out of it.
"Hi," you say. "Okay. That's new."

[free_reign]
After that, the routine changes shape.
School still matters. Work still pays. The store still has what you cannot make.
But now the shed has a voice in it.
Day one starts for real.
